{"declarations":[{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.small_oscillations_about_equilibrium\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">small_oscillations_about_equilibrium</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"Small oscillations about a stable equilibrium orientation are governed by linearised equations\nobtained by expanding energy to second order in angular displacements. Normal modes and\nfrequencies depend on inertia and restoring torques. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.small_oscillations_about_equilibrium","kind":"def","line":235,"name":"RigidBody.small_oscillations_about_equilibrium","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L235-L240"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rigid_body_work_and_power\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">rigid_body_work_and_power</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The power delivered to a rigid body by forces is P = ∑ Fᵢ ⋅ vᵢ = F_tot ⋅ V + M ⋅ ω, where F_tot\nis total force, V the reference point velocity, and M the torque. Translational and rotational\ncontributions separate. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rigid_body_work_and_power","kind":"def","line":228,"name":"RigidBody.rigid_body_work_and_power","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L228-L233"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.reduction_to_two_body\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">reduction_to_two_body</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"If a rigid body is confined to planar motion, its dynamics reduce to a two-dimensional problem:\nthe inertia reduces to a scalar moment and rotation is described\nby a single angular velocity. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.reduction_to_two_body","kind":"def","line":221,"name":"RigidBody.reduction_to_two_body","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L221-L226"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.intermediate_axis_instability\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">intermediate_axis_instability</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"Rotations about the largest and smallest principal axes are stable under small perturbations;\nrotation about the intermediate axis is unstable (tennis-racket effect). ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.intermediate_axis_instability","kind":"def","line":215,"name":"RigidBody.intermediate_axis_instability","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L215-L219"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.steady_rotation_conditions\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">steady_rotation_conditions</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A rigid body can perform steady (uniform) rotation about any principal axis if the torque about\nthat axis vanishes. Stability depends on the ordering of principal moments. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.steady_rotation_conditions","kind":"def","line":209,"name":"RigidBody.steady_rotation_conditions","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L209-L213"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.euler_equations\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">euler_equations</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"When motion is described in body-fixed principal axes (I₁, I₂, I₃ diagonal), the equations of\nrotational motion (Euler’s equations) are:\nI₁ dω₁/dt + (I₃ − I₂) ω₂ ω₃ = M₁, with cyclic permutations.\nM is the external torque about the centre of mass. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.euler_equations","kind":"def","line":201,"name":"RigidBody.euler_equations","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L201-L207"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_for_angular_momentum\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">transport_law_for_angular_momentum</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"For angular momentum, the relation between inertial and rotating derivatives is\n  (dM/dt)_inertial = d'M/dt + Ω × M,\nand with the rotational form of Newton's law M_tot = (dM/dt)_inertial this yields\n  d'M/dt + Ω × M = K,\nthe angular-momentum equation in the rotating frame. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_for_angular_momentum","kind":"def","line":192,"name":"RigidBody.transport_law_for_angular_momentum","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L192-L199"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_for_momentum\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">transport_law_for_momentum</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"For linear momentum, the relation between inertial and rotating derivatives is\n  (dP/dt)_inertial = d'P/dt + Ω × P.\nSo, d'P/dt + Ω × P = F which is the linear-momentum equation in the rotating frame. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_for_momentum","kind":"def","line":185,"name":"RigidBody.transport_law_for_momentum","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L185-L190"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_inertial_rotating\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">transport_law_inertial_rotating</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"For any vector field A(t), its inertial-frame time derivative equals the rotating-frame\nderivative plus the contribution from the frame rotation:\n  (dA/dt)_inertial = (dA/dt)_rotating + Ω × A.\nHere Ω is the angular velocity of the rotating frame. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.transport_law_inertial_rotating","kind":"def","line":177,"name":"RigidBody.transport_law_inertial_rotating","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L177-L183"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rotating_frame_derivative\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">rotating_frame_derivative</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The time derivative in the rotating frame, d'/dt, is the derivative\nof the components of a vector with respect to time when expressed in the\nrotating (body-fixed) frame. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rotating_frame_derivative","kind":"def","line":170,"name":"RigidBody.rotating_frame_derivative","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L170-L175"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.RotatingFrame\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">RotatingFrame</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A rotating body-fixed frame is a coordinate system attached to the body\nthat rotates with the body relative to an inertial (fixed) frame. The frame\nis characterised by its angular velocity vector Ω(t). ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.RotatingFrame","kind":"def","line":163,"name":"RigidBody.RotatingFrame","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L163-L168"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.spherical_top\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">spherical_top</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A spherical top is when all three of the principal moments of inertia are equal. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.spherical_top","kind":"def","line":158,"name":"RigidBody.spherical_top","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L158-L161"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.symmetrical_top\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">symmetrical_top</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A symmetrical top is when only two of the principal moments of inertia are equal. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.symmetrical_top","kind":"def","line":153,"name":"RigidBody.symmetrical_top","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L153-L156"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.asymmetrical_top\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">asymmetrical_top</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"An asymmetrical top is when none of the principal moments of inertia are equal. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.asymmetrical_top","kind":"def","line":148,"name":"RigidBody.asymmetrical_top","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L148-L151"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia_bound\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">principal_axes_of_inertia_bound</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"None of the principal moments of inertia can exceed the sum of other two. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia_bound","kind":"def","line":143,"name":"RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia_bound","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L143-L146"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">principal_axes_of_inertia</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"Because the inertia tensor is real symmetric, there exists an orthonormal basis of principal\naxes in which it is diagonal. The corresponding directions are the principal axes of inertia. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia","kind":"def","line":137,"name":"RigidBody.principal_axes_of_inertia","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L137-L141"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.parallel_axis_theorem\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">parallel_axis_theorem</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"If I_O is the inertia tensor about a point O, then the inertia tensor about a parallel point O'\ndisplaced by a is I_{O'} = I_O + M(|a|² 1 − a ⊗ a). This is the parallel-axis theorem. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.parallel_axis_theorem","kind":"def","line":131,"name":"RigidBody.parallel_axis_theorem","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L131-L135"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.kinetic_energy_decomposition\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">kinetic_energy_decomposition</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The kinetic energy decomposes into translational and rotational parts:\nT = (1/2) M |V|² + (1/2) ω ⋅ I_CM ω.\nHere V is the velocity of the centre of mass and I_CM is the inertia tensor about that point. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.kinetic_energy_decomposition","kind":"def","line":124,"name":"RigidBody.kinetic_energy_decomposition","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L124-L129"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rotational_equation_inertial\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">rotational_equation_inertial</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"In the inertial frame, the rotational equation of motion of a rigid body about the center of\nmass is given by dM/dt = K, where `M` is the total angular momentum and `K` is the total\nexternal torque. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rotational_equation_inertial","kind":"def","line":117,"name":"RigidBody.rotational_equation_inertial","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L117-L122"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.translational_equation_inertial\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">translational_equation_inertial</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"In the inertial frame, the translational equation of motion of a rigid body is given by\ndP/dt = F, where `P` is the total linear momentum and `F` is the total external force acting\non the body. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.translational_equation_inertial","kind":"def","line":110,"name":"RigidBody.translational_equation_inertial","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L110-L115"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.angular_momentum_about_point\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">angular_momentum_about_point</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The total angular momentum about a point O is L = ∫ r × v dm. With v = V + ω × r about the\ncentre of mass, L = R × (M V) + I_CM ω, where R is the centre of mass position. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.angular_momentum_about_point","kind":"def","line":104,"name":"RigidBody.angular_momentum_about_point","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L104-L108"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.center_of_mass_point_moves_as_particle\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">center_of_mass_point_moves_as_particle</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The centre of mass of a rigid body moves as if all mass were concentrated at that\npoint and acted upon by the resultant external force: M a_CM = ∑ F_ext. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.center_of_mass_point_moves_as_particle","kind":"def","line":98,"name":"RigidBody.center_of_mass_point_moves_as_particle","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L98-L102"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.decomposition_of_motion\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">decomposition_of_motion</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The motion of a rigid body can be decomposed into a translation of some reference point plus a\nrotation about that point. There exists a time-dependent vector V(t) and angular velocity ω(t)\nsuch that v(r) = V + ω × r, where r is measured from the reference point. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.decomposition_of_motion","kind":"def","line":91,"name":"RigidBody.decomposition_of_motion","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L91-L96"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.angular_velocity_is_well_defined\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">angular_velocity_is_well_defined</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The angular velocity of rotation of a rigid body from a system of coordinates fixed in the\nbody is independent of the system chosen. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.angular_velocity_is_well_defined","kind":"def","line":85,"name":"RigidBody.angular_velocity_is_well_defined","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L85-L89"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.velocity_decomposition\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">velocity_decomposition</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The velocity v of any point in a rigid body is\nv = V + Ω × r,\nwhere V is the velocity of the origin of the moving system and Ω is the angular velocity. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.velocity_decomposition","kind":"def","line":78,"name":"RigidBody.velocity_decomposition","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L78-L83"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rigid_body_dof\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">rigid_body_dof</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalLemma\">InformalLemma</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"A rigid body in three-dimensional space has six degrees of freedom:\nthree translational (for the position of its centre of mass) and three\nrotational (for its orientation). ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.rigid_body_dof","kind":"def","line":71,"name":"RigidBody.rigid_body_dof","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L71-L76"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.coordinate_system\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">coordinate_system</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"One can describe the motion of rigid body with a fixed (inertial) coordinate system (X,Y,Z)\nand a moving system (x₁,x₂,x₃) rigidly attached to the body. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.coordinate_system","kind":"def","line":65,"name":"RigidBody.coordinate_system","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L65-L69"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.kineticEnergy\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">kineticEnergy</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/Meta/Informal/Basic.html#InformalDefinition\">InformalDefinition</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"The kinetic energy of a rigid body. ","docLink":"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.kineticEnergy","kind":"def","line":60,"name":"RigidBody.kineticEnergy","sourceLink":"https://github.com/HEPLean/PhysLean#L60-L63"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">theorem</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody.inertiaTensor_symmetric\"><span class=\"name\">RigidBody</span>.<span class=\"name\">inertiaTensor_symmetric</span></a></span><span class=\"impl_arg\"><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">{<span class=\"fn\">d</span> : <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Nat\">ℕ</a>}</span></span>\n</span><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">R</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./PhysLean/ClassicalMechanics/RigidBody/Basic.html#RigidBody\">RigidBody</a> <span class=\"fn\">d</span></span>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<spa